ZZ Top - Greatest Hits fits those CD-enthusiast priorities. It is a single-artist compilation in the Classic Rock / Album-Oriented Rock (AOR) category, which usually means consistent sonic character across tracks (similar production values, instrumentation and tonal palette). As a greatest-hits collection from one band, it offers a coherent listening flow and dependable mastering that makes it rewarding to play straight through on a CD player—something many collectors and attentive listeners appreciate. The AOR label also signals music crafted with album listening in mind (tight arrangements, emphasis on production and guitar/drum tones), which showcases what a good CD format can deliver.
I reject 30 #1 Hits because, judging by its genre tags (Rock; Oldies & Retro; Rockabilly) and its generic title, it reads as a broad hits compilation spanning eras and styles. Such compilations often include recordings with varied original masters, inconsistent sonic quality, and abrupt stylistic shifts that reduce cohesion when listened to as an album. For a listener whose primary stated interest is enjoying CDs themselves, that inconsistent listening experience is less desirable than a focused, well-produced single-artist selection. Therefore, ZZ Top - Greatest Hits better aligns with the priorities a CD enthusiast would reasonably use to choose a satisfying disc.

